COME ONE UNCLE SAM'S THANKSGIVING DINNER.
COME
EQUAL
In 1869, political cartoonist Thomas Nast published a cartoon in Harper's Weekly titled “Uncle Sam's Thanksgiving
Dinner." The cartoon shows people of different races, ethnicities, and backgrounds sitting together at a large table
for a Thanksgiving meal. Leading this diverse Thanksgiving Day is Uncle Sam (carving the turkey on the far right)
and Columbia (seated on the far left), the female personification of America. Behind Uncle Sam is a painting of
Castle Garden, which was the main entry point for immigrants to the United States until it was replaced by Ellis
Island in 1890. At a time when the U.S. was recovering from the Civil War and dealing with questions about civil
rights and immigration, this cartoon imagined a country where all people were welcomed and treated equally-an
idea not yet fully realized. Nast was using the cartoon to support the values of unity, equality, and inclusion.
Directions: Look closely at the cartoon and answer the questions below.
1. What message is Thomas Nast trying to send with this cartoon?
2. Who is included at the Thanksgiving table, and why is that important?
3. What do the words "Equal Rights to All Men" mean in the context of 1869?
STUDENTS
OF
HISTORY
4. Why do you think the cartoon uses a Thanksgiving meal to show unity?
5. Do you think the cartoon reflects what life was really like in 1869? Why or why not?
6. Do you feel this image would be controversial to any Americans today? Explain.
Extension
Thomas Nast used a Thanksgiving dinner to show people of different backgrounds coming together in unity. Now it's
your turn to do something similar.
Choose any American holiday (like Fourth of July, Labor Day, Veterans Day, New Year's, etc.) and design a cartoon
that shows people from different backgrounds, cultures, or communities coming together to celebrate. Think about
what message you want to send about inclusion, unity, or equality-just like Nast did in 1869.
Your cartoon should include:
• A clear holiday theme
• At least 3 different groups or types of people
represented
• A setting or symbol that connects to the holiday
• A message or caption that explains the cartoon's
meaning
Be creative! You can use speech bubbles, banners, or signs to help share your message.
